**BLOCK 1 FIX — separate contestant model from referee model (codex):**
`--model` is the PRODUCER (contestant) model: it feeds ONLY bench.ProducerOverrides
(the replay producer identity), NEVER the judge. The judge/referee model is a
SEPARATE input: a NEW `--judge-model` flag with git-config fallback etude.judgeModel
(resolved exactly like --judge/etude.judge resolves the judge command). resolveJudge
takes/resolves BOTH the judge command AND the judge model independently and builds
&eval.ExecJudge{Command: strings.Fields(spec), Model: judgeModel}. If --judge-model
is omitted and etude.judgeModel is unset, ExecJudge.Model is EMPTY (the judge
command may encode its own model — state this in docs and the error path is not
triggered by an empty judge model). Conflating contestant and referee models was a
correctness/clarity defect; they are now fully decoupled.

**Orchestration flow (Q2):** SelectCohort(stage,--last) -> repoRoot(ctx)
(init.go:225) -> build Pipeline{Store, Runner, Judge, Recorder: replay.RunRecorder
{Store, Now}, Seed, Overrides, Now} -> for each cr in result.Selected call
p.BenchRun(ctx, root, cr). SKIP-AND-REPORT (NOT abort): a single BenchRun error is
caught into a failedRuns list ({SourceRunID, error}); loop continues. A cohort tool
must not die on one bad run. result.Skipped (ineligible runs from SelectCohort) is
reported separately from runtime failures. Inject Recorder + now via benchRunner so
tests use a fixed clock (deterministic replay run ids). Pass --seed through to
Pipeline.Seed (folds into the per-pair RNG — see BLOCK 2).

**Win-rate aggregation (Q3):** new internal/bench/aggregate.go,
Aggregate([]BenchOutcome) Report. total = len(successful outcomes). Counts A/B/tie
from Outcome.Winner (CANONICAL A=original, B=replay — already back-mapped by
PairwiseEvaluator before it reaches BenchOutcome.Winner). Headline = win_rate_B =
(countB + 0.5*countTie)/total — HIGH means the NEW skill (replay) beats original.
NOTE (Opus, anti-regression): eval.go's doc comment documents win_rate_A =
(A + 0.5*tie)/total; bench's headline is its COMPLEMENT (win_rate_B = 1 - win_rate_A
when no missing data). This is intentional (we want "new skill win rate"); add a
code comment citing eval.go so a future reader does not "fix" it back to win_rate_A.
Guard total==0: Report.Total==0; CLI prints "no successful evaluations", exits
non-zero. Report carries WinRateB float, CountA/CountB/CountTie/Total ints, plus the
per-run outcomes + failure/skip lists for rendering.

**Report format (Q4):** human text to stdout via tabwriter (run.go:83 idiom).
- Header: "bench <stage>: replay (new skill) wins NN.N% vs original" + line
  "(B=<n> A=<n> tie=<n>) over <total> evals; <skipped> skipped, <failed> failed".
- Per-run table: SOURCE RUN | REPLAY RUN | WINNER | CONF | EVAL ID | FINDING (first
  finding message, or "-").
- Skipped section: source run id + SkipReason + Detail.
- Failed section: source run id + error message.
Orientation stated explicitly so a high % is unambiguous.

**Errors + exit codes (Q5):**
- last<=0 -> error, exit 1 (before any work).
- no runner / no judge command -> error, exit 1 (before any work). Empty judge
  MODEL is NOT an error (see BLOCK 1).
- cohort empty (zero Selected) -> error "no runs contain stage \"<s>\" with a
  replayable output", exit 1.
- All selected runs failed (total==0, all in failedRuns) -> render failures, return
  error (exit non-zero).
- Partial failure (some succeed) -> exit 0; failures shown in report.

**BLOCK 2 FIX — determinism vs the per-pair presentation swap (Opus):**
VERIFIED in internal/eval/pairwiseevaluator.go: evaluateSingle (l.63) calls
perPairSwap (l.137) which derives a per-pair swap from Seed + each target's pairKey
(Source.Artifact, else Role+":"+sha256(Content)); buildJudgeRequest (l.201) then
presents the two targets with NEUTRAL roles "left" (first) and "right" (second),
hiding which is original/replay; mapWinnerBack (l.182) converts the judge's
POSITION-relative winner back to canonical A/B. So a judge that blindly emits
{"winner":"B"} is position-relative and yields a non-deterministic canonical mix
across pairs/seeds. FIX = make judge doubles AND judge.sh CONTENT-AWARE so the
canonical outcome is deterministic regardless of presentation order:
- The judge sees JudgeRequest.Targets = [{Role:"left",Content:first},
  {Role:"right",Content:second}]. ExecJudge materializes these into ETUDE_INPUTS_DIR
  as 00-target-left and 01-target-right (exec_judge.go fmt "%02d-target-%s" over
  req.Targets). The content-aware judge keys off CONTENT, not position.
- Test seam: seed the REPLAY output bytes with a unique marker the original bytes
  lack (e.g. stub runner emits "<<REPLAY>>" + input bytes; original captured output
  has no such marker). Content-aware stub Judge reads jr.Targets[].Content, finds
  which presented side contains "<<REPLAY>>" (= canonical B), and returns
  POSITION-relative winner so that after mapWinnerBack the CANONICAL winner is what
  the test intends. To assert an exact A/B/tie MIX across N runs: vary the marker
  per source run (e.g. replay carries "<<WIN:B>>" / "<<WIN:A>>" / "<<WIN:TIE>>"
  injected by a per-run stub runner) and have the stub Judge emit the position-
  relative winner that back-maps to that canonical verdict. Because the stub reads
  Content, the per-pair swap is irrelevant and the canonical mix is deterministic;
  assert exact CountA/CountB/CountTie and win_rate_B. Confirmed: eval.StubJudge only
  returns Canned, so use a TEST-LOCAL Judge (implements eval.Judge) that inspects
  jr.Targets[].Content — NOT eval.StubJudge and NOT a verdicts[i++] sequence (a
  position-blind sequence would NOT survive back-mapping).
- Manual test: judge.sh inspects ETUDE_INPUTS_DIR/00-target-left and
  01-target-right, greps for the replay marker, and prints the position-relative
  winner so the canonical winner is deterministic. (Alternatives, NOT chosen:
  pin --seed and hand-compute perPairSwap per pair; or assert only total/skipped/
  failed and document the headline % as non-deterministic. Content-aware is most
  robust and is what this plan uses.)

